# Shared Root-Cause Issue Group Pattern

## When to Apply

When investigating a bug and discovering that **multiple open issues share the same root cause** (e.g., missing validation layer, misconfigured middleware, incorrect shared utility), follow this protocol:

## Protocol

### 1. Identify & Group
- Search existing issues for the same symptom pattern (`gh issue list --state all --search "..."`)
- Determine the shared root cause
- List all affected issues as a **group**

### 2. Cross-Comment (AS-IS / TO-BE)
Add a comment to **every issue in the group** containing:

```markdown
## AS-IS / TO-BE Analysis
### AS-IS (현재 상태)
- [Root cause description]
- [Specific symptom in this issue]

### TO-BE (목표 상태)
- [Solution description]
- [Expected behavior after fix]

### Related Issues (관련 이슈)
- #NNN — [title] (현재 이슈)
- #NNN — [title]
...

### Resolution Plan
[Single fix resolves N issues simultaneously]
Branch: `fix/NNN-description`
```

### 3. Single Branch, Single Fix
- Create ONE branch addressing the root cause
- Name it after the **primary** (most severe or first-filed) issue
- Reference ALL group issues in the PR description and commit messages

### 4. Before/After Verification
After implementing the fix (`github-issue-evidence`):
- Use **one** directory: `issues/{primary-N}/` with `group.md` listing all related issues
- **Before**: `before/{related-N}-{slug}.png` per issue scenario (capture before code change)
- **After**: `after/{related-N}-{slug}.png` per scenario (same steps after fix)
- Test each issue's specific scenario individually
- Cross-comment on every issue with paths under `issues/{primary-N}/`
- Close all issues in the group from the single PR

### 5. Downstream / Consumer Compatibility Check
When a shared fix changes an interface (API response, event payload, config schema, etc.):
- Verify all consumers still work with the new shape
- Check for hardcoded assumptions in callers (field names, error codes, etc.)
- Test error-handling paths in downstream modules

## Anti-Patterns to Avoid
- ❌ Fixing one issue at a time when they share a root cause (creates incomplete fixes)
- ❌ Closing issues without Before/After evidence
- ❌ Changing a shared interface without checking all consumers
- ❌ Creating duplicate fix branches for the same root cause
